Cryptography:

This is the process of »Breaking« codes or ciphers.

I have written out some information which might be helpful for all you 
code crackers out there.....


FREQUENCY TABLE:
================

"In language, certain letters are used more than others..."

If you check the above statement you will see that the letter E features
predominantly. In fact the amount of times letters are used are:

E = featured 8 times
A = featured 5 times
R = featured 5 times
T = featured 4 times
N = featured 4 times
S = featured 3 times
L = featured 2 times
G = featured 2 times
I = featured 2 times
H = featured 2 times
O = featured 2 times
M = featured 1 time
U = featured 1 time 
C = featured 1 time
D = featured 1 time

This is almost correct to the LETTER FREQUENCY TABLE (LFT)...
The LFT is a table which shows how many times letters are used in a piece
of text...

Most of the time the frequency table will appear as this:

ETAONRISHDLFCMUGYPWBVKXJQZ

^                        ^
|                        |
|                        `--- LETTERS AT THIS END FEATURE THE LEAST
|
`---- LETTERS AT THIS END FEATURE THE MOST

You can use this when trying to break a cipher, by picking out which words
feature the most and matching them with the frequency table which most of
the time will be correct.

LETTER COMBINATIONS:
====================

When trying to break a cipher, look out for letters that are grouped together.
These combinations will appear frequently in words.

Common combinations are:

   TH  <------ Combinations at the top here appear most frequently
   HE
   AN
   RE
   ER
   IN
   ON
   AT
   ND
   ST
   ES
   EN
   OF
   TE
   ED
   OR
   TI
   HI
   AS
   TO
   WH  <------ Combinations at the bottom here appear least frequently   


You can also find combinations of letters that are doubled...
Words such as lOOk and liTTle fit in this category:

The most common are:

     LL  <------ Combinations at the top here appear most frequently
     EE
     SS
     OO
     TT
     FF
     RR
     NN
     PP
     CC  <------ Combinations at the bottom here appear least frequently


1 AND 2 LETTER WORDS:
=====================

There are two one letter words which will be quite visible: A and I

The most common two letter words are:

     OF  <------ Combinations at the top here appear most frequently
     TO
     IN
     IT
     IS
     BE
     AS
     AT
     SO
     WE
     HE
     BY
     OR
     ON
     DO
     IF
     ME
     MY
     UP
     AN  <------ Combinations at the bottom here appear least frequently

SIGNATURES:
===========

Look out for people who have signed their message in code!!

If you know the person's name and their is a visible encoded signature then
you can get the letters for their name just by looking at the signature!



                      AN EXAMPLE DECRYPTION SEQUENCE
                ------==========##########==========------


I will now decode a message before your very eyes...even though I know
what the message is I will break it by examining it!

This message was encoded using the Keyboard1.code.

MESSAGE BEGINS:

Itssg zitkt. O qd q ztlz dtllqut ziqz iql wttf vkozztf zg ltt oy O eqf wt
rteohitktr wn Lztct Iqmtss zit hkgukqddtk gy ziol yoft hotet gy vgka.
O ight ngx eqf ltt viqz ol ugofu gf itkt vozi zit rteohitkofu. Oy fgz zitf
egfzqez dt wn t-dqos. Dn qrrktll ytqzxktl gf zit egfztfzl hqut.
Qfnvqn, tfgxui gy dn fqzztkofu. Gf vozi zit rtegrofu.

                                        Lztct Iqmtss

MESSAGE ENDS

Okay...let's have a look at what we have...My name is Steve Hazell and I 
wrote the message so we already have my signature at the bottom of the 
message.

So let's make a list of letters

"Lztct Iqmtss" must be "Steve Hazell" -  You see how many letters we already 
                                         have?

L = S
Z = T
T = E
C = V
I = H         That's a total of 8 letters from the 26 of the alphabet...
Q = A         Pretty good...just from the error of leaving a signature!!
M = Z
S = L

I'll now take another look at the message...

MESSAGE BEGINS:

Itssg zitkt. @{b}O@{ub} qd @{b}q@{ub} ztlz dtllqut ziqz iql wttf vkozztf zg ltt oy O eqf wt
rteohitktr wn Lztct Iqmtss zit hkgukqddtk gy ziol yoft hotet gy vgka.
O ight ngx eqf ltt viqz ol ugofu gf itkt vozi zit rteohitkofu. Oy fgz zitf
egfzqez dt wn t-dqos. Dn qrrktll ytqzxktl gf zit egfztfzl hqut.
Qfnvqn, tfgxui gy dn fqzztkofu. Gf vozi zit rtegrofu.

                                        Lztct Iqmtss
MESSAGE ENDS

If you look where I have highlighted, you will see two words with only one
letter.

They are: "O" and "Q" 

They must be either "A" or "I" as they are the only 1 letter words.
We already have the letter "A" from the signature...so "O" must be "I"
So let's add that to our list

L = S
Z = T
T = E
C = V
I = H
Q = A
M = Z
S = L
O = I

We can now begin to edit the message, filling in the old letters with our
new ones.

MESSAGE BEGINS:

@{b}Hell@{ub}g @{b}the@{ub}k@{b}e@{ub}. @{b}I a@{ub}d @{b}a test@{ub} d@{b}essa@{ub}u@{b}e t@{ub}i@{b}at has@{ub} w@{b}ee@{ub}f vk@{b}itte@{ub}f @{b}t@{ub}g l@{b}ee@{ub} @{b}i@{ub}y @{b}I@{ub} e@{b}a@{ub}f w@{b}e@{ub}
r@{b}e@{ub}e@{b}i@{ub}h@{b}he@{ub}k@{b}e@{ub}r wn @{b}Steve Hazell the @{ub}hkguk@{b}a@{ub}dd@{b}e@{ub}k gy @{b}th@{ub}o@{b}s@{ub} y@{b}i@{ub}f@{b}e@{ub} h@{b}ei@{ub}e@{b}e@{ub} gy vgka.
@{b}I@{ub} @{b}h@{ub}gh@{b}e@{ub} ngx e@{b}a@{ub}f l@{b}ee@{ub} v@{b}ha@{ub}z @{b}is@{ub} ug@{b}i@{ub}fu gf @{b}he@{ub}k@{b}e@{ub} v@{b}ith the r@{b}e@{ub}e@{b}i@{ub}h@{b}eh@{ub}k@{b}i@{ub}fu. @{b}I@{ub}y fgz @{b}the@{ub}f
egf@{b}t@{ub}qe@{b}t@{ub} d@{b}e@{ub} wn @{b}e@{ub}-d@{b}ail@{ub}. Dn @{b}a@{ub}rrk@{b}e@{ub}ll y@{b}eat@{ub}xk@{b}e@{ub}l gf @{b}the@{ub} egf@{b}te@{ub}f@{b}e@{ub}l h@{b}q@{ub}u@{b}e@{ub}.
Qfnv@{b}a@{ub}n, @{b}e@{ub}fgxu@{b}h@{ub} gy dn f@{b}atte@{ub}k@{b}i@{ub}fu. Gf v@{b}ith the @{ub}r@{b}e@{ub}egr@{b}i@{ub}fu.

                                        @{b}Steve Hazell@{ub}

MESSAGE ENDS

If you look at the word e-dail you can see that the letter d is still in its original 
code form. It is a fairly safe bet to think that D = m (e-mail).

I wont do the rest...I think I have given you a fairly good lead...you can
finish it...

Just use the rules...and most of all...common sense.


ENCRYPTION TECHNIQUES
=====================

Alot of people can decrypt a message by simply reading it once...

This is because they can see the structure of the text (as above)...

To avoid this...use the "REMOVE SPACES" function...that way whoever tries
to decode your message will not be able to rely on words!

This also means whoever you sent your message to will have a piece of text with
no spaces...but they can easily copy out the text again...adding spaces as they
go.

Another technique is to write the sentences backwards (using the reverse function).

This also helps to confuse!

TIP: USE ONE METHOD AFTER ANOTHER - IE:ENCIPHERING @{b}THEN@{ub} REVERSING!!!

